The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | IFC funds for Tata Power 
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       IFC funds for Tata Power 
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 9: The International Finance Corporation (IFC) will give a $450-million assistance to Tata Powers mega power project at Mundhra, Gujarat.        
	The first of the plants 800MW units is expected to be commissioned in mid-2011. The other units will be launched at four-month intervals.        
	The 4,000MW project, which the Tatas had won through a competitive bidding process, will create 5,000 jobs during construction and 700 jobs once it becomes operational.        
	Of the total project cost of $4.2 billion, the IFC will provide $450 million with a repayment period 20 years, an IFC release said.         
	Long-term financing will improve the risk profile of the project and facilitate funding from local banks of around 15 years maturity, it added.        
	Other lenders assisting the project are the Asian Development Bank, which will also give $450 million, and Korean ECA, which will provide $800 million.         
	The local banks will lend $1.5 billion. Theres also an equity component of $1 billion.        
	The project will supply electricity to 1.6 crore domestic consumers apart from industrial and agricultural users, the release said.                          
	According to the release, the use of super-critical technology will make Mundra power project Indias most efficient coal-fired plant.        
	The government has planned to set up nine ultra-mega power projects, of which three have been awarded and a fourth is in the process of being bid out. Reliance power has bagged the Sasan and Krishnapatnam projects.                                                                                                                                     
